Anthony Boogert is a senior associate in the Mergers & Acquisitions Group in the Sydney office of King & Wood Mallesons. Mr. Boogert represents financial sponsors, corporate clients and investment banks in a variety of domestic and cross-border transactions, including mergers and acquisitions, joint ventures, securities offerings and debt restructurings. Mr. Boogert previously worked in the New York office of Skadden, Aprs, Slate, Meagher & Flom LLP.

Significant representations in which Mr. Boogert has been involved include:

 • Transurban Queensland on its A$1.87 billion acquisition of AirportlinkM7;

 • Deutsche Bank, AG in connection with its investment in the consortium vehicle which was the successful bidder for GE Capital‘s Australian and New Zealand consumer lending arm (Latitude Financial Services) for A$8.2 billion;

 • Australian Unity Limited on their A$250 million floating rate 'Simple Corporate Bond' (the first issuance under the 'Simple Corporate Bond' legislation);

 • Costa Group Holdings Limited on its A$551 million initial public offering and listing on the ASX, following a dual-track sale process;

 • Sprint Nextel Corporation in its US$21.6 billion acquisition by SoftBank Corp. (named as the “Global M&A Deal of the Year: Grand Prize” by The American Lawyer) and its US$3.6 billion acquisition of Clearwire Corporation. Both transactions were recognized in the Corporate & Commercial category in the Financial Times’ 2013 U.S. “Innovative Lawyers” report;

• Travelport Limited and Travelport Holdings Limited on various debt restructuring transactions;

• the underwriters and initial purchasers for various equity and debt offerings by The Carlyle Group L.P.;

• Western Asset Mortgage Capital Corporation (an affiliate of WAMCO) on its initial public offering; and

• the underwriters for the US$530 million initial public offering of Delphi Automotive PLC.

